04231nam a22005535i 9780674269781DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742697817 a10.4159/97806742697812doi  a(DE-B1597)600632  a(OCoLC)1272994268  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHM1131b.S554 2021 7aPHI0080002bisacsh04a179/.92231 aSmith, David Livingstone, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Monsters :bThe Uncanny Power of Dehumanization /cDavid Livingstone Smith. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Something Like a Darkness -- t1. What Is Dehumanization? -- t2. Dehumanization Is Real -- t3. In the Blood -- t4. Essential Differences -- t5. The Logic of Race -- t6. Hierarchy -- t7. The Order of Things -- t8. Being Human -- t9. Ideology -- t10. Dehumanization as Ideology -- t11. Ambivalence -- t12. Making Monsters -- t13. Last Words and Loose Ends -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA leading scholar explores what it means to dehumanize others—and how and why we do it. “I wouldn’t have accepted that they were human beings. You would see an infant who’s just learning to smile, and it smiles at you, but you still kill it.” So a Hutu man explained to an incredulous researcher, when asked to recall how he felt slaughtering Tutsis in Rwanda in 1994. Such statements are shocking, yet we recognize them; we hear their echoes in accounts of genocides, massacres, and pogroms throughout history. How do some people come to believe that their enemies are monsters, and therefore easy to kill? In Making Monsters David Livingstone Smith offers a poignant meditation on the philosophical and psychological roots of dehumanization. Drawing on harrowing accounts of lynchings, Smith establishes what dehumanization is and what it isn’t. When we dehumanize our enemy, we hold two incongruous beliefs at the same time: we believe our enemy is at once subhuman and fully human. To call someone a monster, then, is not merely a resort to metaphor—dehumanization really does happen in our minds. Turning to an abundance of historical examples, Smith explores the relationship between dehumanization and racism, the psychology of hierarchy, what it means to regard others as human beings, and why dehumanizing others transforms them into something so terrifying that they must be destroyed. Meticulous but highly readable, Making Monsters suggests that the process of dehumanization is deeply seated in our psychology. It is precisely because we are all human that we are vulnerable to the manipulations of those trading in the politics of demonization and violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHate. 0aHumanityxPsychological aspects. 0aLynching. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aRespect for persons. 0aToleration. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Good & Evil.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067426978140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269781/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles